{
  "answer": "Both Ghalib and Iqbal treat the naala/nawa not as mere sound but as something that undergoes a physical or ontological transformation — yet the direction and logic of that transformation differ sharply.\n\n**Ghalib — naala as compressed physical substance (Diwan-E-Ghalib, chapters 18 and 138)**\n\nThe primary couplet is in chapter 138 ('Milti hai khuu-e-yaar se naar iltihaab mein'):\n  > 'Woh naala dil mein khas ke baraabar jagah na paaye / Jis naale se shigaaf pade aaftaab mein'\n  > Translation: 'A sigh so strong it could have split the sun … finds not the slightest foothold in a heart that does not care.'\n\nGhalib gives the naala physical dimensionality: it takes up space (or fails to), it has a force sufficient to fracture the sun. The transformation here is paradoxical inward compression — the lament powerful enough to crack the cosmos cannot find even a mote of straw's worth of room inside the indifferent beloved's heart. The naala is not merely uttered; it is a material that presses against walls.\n\nChapter 18 ('Be-e'tedaaliyon se subuk sab mein hum huay') extends this further:\n  > 'Ajzaa-e-naala dil mein mere rizq-e-hum huay' — 'the fragments/particles of the lament became food for grief inside my heart.'\n  > 'Naale adam mein chand hamare supurd thay / Jo waan na khinch sake so woh yaan aa ke dam huay' — 'Some laments were entrusted to non-existence; those that could not stay there came back and became my breath.'\n\nHere the naala undergoes two distinct transformations: (1) it shatters into 'ajzaa' (particles) and these particles become the very nourishment that sustains grief — the lament feeds the wound it expresses, a self-perpetuating loop; and (2) laments consigned to non-being (adam) re-enter life as the poet's own breath. Naala transforms into the matter of life itself, but through a circuit of frustration and return.\n\n**Iqbal — nawa as latent potential released toward elevation (Bang-E-Dara Part 2, chapter 19, 'Nawa-e-Gham')**\n\nIqbal's central metaphor is the silent rabab (lute): 'Zindagani Hai meri misl-e-rabaab-e-khamosh / Jis Ki har rang ke naghmon se hai labrez aaghosh' — 'My life is like a silent, waiting lute / whose bosom holds all songs, though they are mute.' Every string contains 'sainkron naghmon ke mazaar' — tombs of hundreds of melodies. The nawa-e-gham is stored inside, not yet sounded.\n\nTransformation requires a divine external catalyst: 'naseem-e-chaman-e-Toor' — the breeze from the garden of Sinai (the site of Moses's revelation) — which gently plucks 'taar-e-hayaat' (the string of life) and frees the soul imprisoned within. Once released, the faint song of sorrow ('naghma-e-yaas') rises and becomes 'baang-e-dara' (the call/bell of the marching caravan) — the communal cry that drives weeping souls forward.\n\nThe closing couplet delivers the key transformation: 'Jis Tarah rif'at-e-shabnam hai mazaaq-e-ram se / Meri Fitrat ki bulandi hai nawa-e-gham se' — 'As dew is raised by its desire for flight / My nature's elevation comes through the melody of sorrow.' The nawa-e-gham is not the wound; it is the mechanism of ascent. Sorrow is the vehicle of transcendence for the self.\n\n**Comparison of the transformations:**\n\n1. Direction: Ghalib's naala turns inward — compressed, fragmented, consumed by the grief it expressed or reconstituted as breath through the circuit of non-being. Iqbal's nawa-e-gham moves outward and upward — from interior silence through divine touch to communal call to personal elevation.\n\n2. Agency: In Ghalib, the naala is acted upon by the beloved's coldness and by the walls of the self; it is suppressed or shattered. In Iqbal, the nawa waits as potential and is activated by a divine breath from Sinai; its eventual release is purposive.\n\n3. Paradox vs. teleology: Ghalib's figure is fundamentally paradoxical — the cosmic force that cannot find room; the self-feeding lament. Iqbal's figure is teleological — suffering is stored, then unlocked, then becomes the very height of the self's nature.\n\n4. Social dimension: Ghalib's naala is locked within the individual poet's interiority or rebounds from the beloved. Iqbal's nawa becomes 'baang-e-dara' for a caravan — the private grief converts into a collective marching cry.\n\nIn short: Ghalib transforms lament into paradoxical matter (it can crack the sun but has no space; it fragments into food for grief; it rebounds from non-being as breath). Iqbal transforms lament into upward force — the compressed silence of the rabab-self, once touched by the divine, becomes the call that leads the caravan and constitutes the self's spiritual ascent.",
